				<p  class="block-text">
					This experiment is designed to gauge your intuitions on how certain adjectives relate to each other. You will be presented with a set of up to twenty adjectives which all relate to a particular attribute. You will see a similar display to the one shown below. It contains a gradient scale ranging from least intense on the left to most intense on the right, with a label indicating the attribute in question at the top (in this case, it's 'size', meaning that the left end of the slider is for the 'smallest' adjectives, while the right end is meant for the 'largest'). The adjectives, listed below the slider, are each represented by a colorful dot. Your task is to arrange these adjectives according to their intensity. For instance, let's say three of your adjectives are "big", "huge", and "enormous". Well, since these all seem to describe "larger" objects (as opposed to, say, "small", "tiny", and "little"), you would put these on the right-hand side of the scale, marked "more".
				</p>
				<br>
				<hr>
				<img src="images/slider1.png" width="600"/>
				<br>
				<br>
				<hr>
				<br>
				<p class="block-text">
					As for <i>where</i> on the right-hand side to place these three, you might think of how you might describe the relationship in words: 'huge' describes something that is larger than 'big', but smaller than 'enormous'." If such a statement feels accurate, then you should arrange them in that order on the slider, with 'big' slightly right-of-center, 'enormous' to the far right, and 'huge' lying somewhere between them. <b>You can also place two adjectives in the same position</b>, if you believe they describe similar qualities, or you can't distinguish between them. For instance, with the adjectives "big" and "large", you might find it difficult to decide which of these is "larger", in which case you can place them in the same position. <b>If you can't think of a good reason to place an adjective on its own, it's usually best to place it in a group with others</b>
				</p>
